{
"explanation": "The defendant committed a serious breach of fiduciary duty by abusing their position as an accountant to embezzle $25,000. While the court considers the defendant's lack of a prior criminal record and the partial restitution as significant mitigating factors demonstrating remorse, the intentional nature of the theft to cover personal debts necessitates more than just probation. The outburst by a courtroom spectator was disregarded, as sentencing must be based on law and facts rather than public sentiment. A 12-month sentence provides a necessary deterrent for white-collar crimes while acknowledging the defendant's first-time offender status.",
"verdict": 12
}
